I went to this appt a month ago and can now share with you since one of the possible diagnoses was PUPPS (pregnancy hives). This was the first time a doctor thought I had PUPPS because the exposure to poison oak from my first major skin reaction was prior to ovulation (I know this because since I had not started my period again yet, we were tracking using ovulation sticks to get pregnant). Typically PUPPS does not start until after the pregnancy is established aka after implantation (when a fertilized egg(s) implants into the uterine lining).

I tested positive for all environmental allergens, except for mold, but pregnancy can skew results. This was very frustrating and nerve wracking because we just moved to be closer to nature. But I do feel a lot of mental and physical relief now because we changed out our soap and detergent that had any tree oils and plant-based ingredients I tested positive for, which has helped my skin a lot. Iâ€™m outside everyday and thankfully being in nature, sitting/walking barefoot in grass, and being surrounded by vegetation has not exacerbated any of my symptoms. 

I also did a blood panel for autoimmune disorders and will share results when I know more. My current hypothesis is that the original exposure to airborne poison oak was possibly exacerbated by an influx of early pregnancy hormones and the adjusted treatment plan due to possible pregnancy. The severity of the reaction triggered my body and Iâ€™ve been in inflammatory mode ever since, which triggered PUPPS. Itâ€™s also possible I could have gotten PUPPS regardless and the timing just aligned this way. I had minor hives sporadically during my last 2 pregnancies, but nothing even close to this.

My new allergist is really unsure and said to just wait until I deliver and see if I still have hives ğŸ˜‘ I am losing hope anyone can provide concrete answers. But Iâ€™m grateful that my skin has improved a lot since this video!

Thank you to those who have been following along with this skin journey sharing advice, telling your own stories, and supporting us in your kind words. It has made me feel encouraged, more connected to you, and lifted up in your love!

Actress Naomi Watts attended the 2024 Met Gala in a custom Balenciaga Tablecloth Couture Dress, which was upcycled from a black lace garment embroidered with jet beads and sequins.

The bustier dress, made of a floral crochet tablecloth measuring 2.1 meters in length and 1.5 meters in diameter, was a reinterpretation of Look 63 from Summer 24. 
Â 
The padded stola worn over the dress is made of black double satin, with an exaggerated filling that sculpts the overall look. For the stola, sustainability is essential, with a conscious choice to use an eco-friendly filling instead of feathers. Â 
Made of jet beads and sequins stacked in an irregular manner around the tableclothâ€™s cut-outs, the embroidery was hand-rendered by the Paris-based Atelier Montex, a venture founded in 1949 with a unique savoir-faire regarding high fashion embroideries.
Â 
The gown features lace that is delicately intertwined with sequins, jet beads, and black crystals. These all mirror the vintage tableclothâ€™s complex pattern. Each element contributes to a richly textured surface, and each recalls CristÃ³bal Balenciagaâ€™s Spanish heritage. 
Â 
Over 600 hours of meticulous embroidery brought this vision to life.
Â 
The overall styling nods to Look 135 from CristÃ³bal Balenciagaâ€™s 1961 Spring/Summer collection, and it also nods to the partyâ€™s dress code: The Garden of Time.

Use this Chinese cooking technique to prepare the best tasting shrimp of your life! The baking soda improves the texture and tenderness of shrimp, the salt keeps it moist while itâ€™s cooking, and sugar helps encourage better, faster browning and caramelization ğŸ¤ğŸ¤ğŸ¤

Cook your rice and marinate the shrimp the night before to get the extra benefit of resistant starch and your meal coming together in less than 10 minutesâœ¨

RECIPE
Ingredients:
-20 pieces of shrimp, peeled and deveined (I butterflied them for presentation purposes)
-1 tsp baking soda
-1 tbsp kosher salt
-2 tbsp sugar
-1 cup ice water
-1 cup ice
-2 tbsp cooking oil (I used avocado) 

seasoning:
-1 tbsp olive oil
-1 tsp garlic powder
-1 tsp sweet paprika
-pinch of salt
-black pepper

sauce:
-2 tbsp mayo (preferably Japanese)
-2 tsp Sriracha
-1 tsp rice vinegar
-1 tsp coconut aminos
-1/4 tsp sesame oil

others:
I served mine with some rice, spinach, edamame, cucumbers, avocado, toasted sesame seeds, and spring onion
but you can enjoy these shrimp on their own, on top of pasta or rice, in salads, wraps, etc!

Method:
1. Place the shrimp (already peeled, deveined and if you want, butterflied) in a large bowl.
2. Add the baking soda, salt, and sugar then mix well.
3. Add the water and ice, then cover and let it marinate in the refrigerator for at least an hour (to overnight).
4. Strain and rinse the shrimp a couple of times. Add olive oil and seasoning (you can do whatever  seasoning you like here).
5. Heat up 1 tbsp oil in a frying pan over medium high heat. Cook your shrimp for 30-60 seconds on each side (it depends on the size and thickness of the shrimp- watch not to overcook!). I cooked them in 2 portions, adding 1 tbsp of oil in-between to not overcrowd the pan. 
6. Plate them, add the other veggies/grains and sauce then enjoy!

Fluffy Dinner Rolls (via @melskitchencafe)
Ingredients
- 1 Â¼ cups milk
- Â¼ cup water
- 4 Tbsp salted butter, at room temperature or melted, plus more for brushing
- 2 Tbsp granulated sugar
- 1 Tbsp instant or active dry yeast
- 1 large egg
- 1 Â¼ tsp salt
- 4 Â¼ to 4 Â½ cups AP flour
.
Instructions:
1. Heat milk in a saucepan over medium heat until milk is steaming. Pour into the bowl of your stand mixer fitted with the dough hook.
2. Add water, 4 Tbsp butter, and sugar. Let mixture cool until warm, 105-110â„‰ on an instant-read thermometer.
3. Stir in yeast and let rest for 5-7 mins until mixture is foamy.
4. Add egg, salt, and flour, starting with 3 Â¾ to 4 cups flour, and mix, adding additional flour gradually, just until dough clears the sides of the bowl and forms a soft, sticky ball. Donâ€™t over flour the dough.
5. Knead for 5-6 mins, until dough is soft and smooth.
6. Cover and let rise in a warm spot until doubled, ~1 hour.
7. Grease a 9x13 inch pan and set aside, lightly punch down the dough and turn out onto a lightly greased countertop.
8. Divide dough into 12 equal pieces. Roll each piece into a ball and place in the prepared pan, spacing Â½ inch or so apart (four rows of three rolls.)
9. Cover with greased plastic wrap or with a towel and let rise until doubled, ~1 hour. The rolls should be very puffy with the sides touching.
10. Preheat the oven to 375â„‰. Place an oven rack in the middle position.
11. Bake rolls for 15-20 mins, until golden on top and bottom. Brush the tops of the rolls with additional melted butter immediately after removing them from the oven. Serve warm or let cool completely on the pan.
12. Yum.

Savoury Oatmeal changed my life ğŸ˜„ This breakfast is a good source of fibre, protein and gut healthy probiotics- a great way to start the day! Thank you for the inspiration @jamesyworld

Kimchi Oatmeal recipe
Ingredients:
*1/2 medium yellow onion, chopped
*2 garlic cloves, minced
*1/2 cup drained Napa cabbage kimchi, chopped
*1/2 cup old-fashioned rolled oats
*1 tbsp coconut aminos (or soy sauce)
*3/4 cup of water
*1 egg
*1 tbsp neutral oil (I used avocado)
*1 tsp sesame oil
*handful of spinach
*1/2 cup shredded mozzarella cheese
*spring onion or scallions (optional topping- I suggest spring onion because itâ€™s lighter tasting, scallions have a sharper flavour but I didnâ€™t have any spring onion) 
*toasted sesame seeds (optional topping)
*chilli oil (optional topping)

*you can use vegan kimchi & cheese, then skip on the egg to make this vegan 

Method
1. Heat up 1 tbsp of neutral oil in a pot over medium high heat. Add the onion and fry until soft/translucent (~3 min)
2. Add the garlic, fry for 30 seconds
3. Add the kimchi, fry for ~4 minutes until it softens
4. Add the oats, mix everything together. Add the water and coconut aminos (or soy sauce), bring to a boil then reduce heat to low. Stir occasionally until it reaches your desired oatmeal texture.
5. Crack in an egg then stir until it is cooked and combined with the rest of the oatmeal.
6. Turn off the heat, add the sesame oil and spinach. Stir to combine.
7. Plate the oatmeal then add the mozzarella. 
8. Cook in the microwave until the cheese is melted (~1 minute)
9. Garnish with spring onion, sesame seeds, and chilli oil
